{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658798"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:55:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:55:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20819"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20819","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20819"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.18,0.64,0.09,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13694"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96210"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13694"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20819"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78930"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11223"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"12651"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32979"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32980"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96210","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96210"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents with abdominal pain, bloody diarrhoea, and hepatomegaly. He recently returned from a six-month volunteer trip in rural Africa where he frequently swam in freshwater lakes. Liver biopsy reveals granulomas containing eggs with lateral spines, surrounded by eosinophils, macrophages, and lymphocytes. There is evidence of periportal fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following parasitic infections is most likely responsible for these findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cysticercosis","Leishmaniasis","Schistosomiasis","Strongyloidiasis","Trichinosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and histopathological findings are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003ESchistosomiasis\u003C/strong\u003E. The key features include granulomatous inflammation around parasite eggs in the liver, with eosinophils being prominent in the inflammatory response. The periportal fibrosis is consistent with early pipe-stem fibrosis. The history of freshwater exposure in an endemic area is a classic risk factor, as humans become infected when larval forms (cercariae) penetrate the skin during contact with infested water.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeishmaniasis\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by protozoan parasites transmitted by sandflies. It typically presents with cutaneous lesions, visceral disease (fever, weight loss, hepatosplenomegaly), or mucocutaneous manifestations. Liver histology would show parasitized macrophages rather than granulomas around eggs.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStrongyloidiasis\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by the nematode \u003Cem\u003EStrongyloides stercoralis\u003C/em\u003E. It typically causes abdominal pain, diarrhoea, and eosinophilia, but liver granulomas are not a characteristic feature. The parasite primarily affects the intestinal mucosa and can cause hyperinfection syndrome in immunocompromised hosts.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECysticercosis\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by larval cysts of \u003Cem\u003ETaenia solium\u003C/em\u003E and primarily affects the central nervous system, skeletal muscle, and subcutaneous tissues. Liver involvement is uncommon, and the histopathology would show cysticerci rather than granulomas around eggs.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrichinosis\u003C/strong\u003E is caused by \u003Cem\u003ETrichinella\u003C/em\u003E species and primarily affects skeletal muscle. While it can cause gastrointestinal symptoms in early infection, the characteristic pathology involves encysted larvae in striated muscle, not granulomas in the liver.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn schistosomiasis, particularly with \u003Cem\u003ES. mansoni\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003ES. japonicum\u003C/em\u003E infections, eggs deposited in tissues trigger granulomatous inflammation. Over time, this leads to fibrosis, particularly in the liver (pipe-stem fibrosis), which can result in portal hypertension, splenomegaly, and esophageal varices. \u003Cem\u003ES. haematobium\u003C/em\u003E primarily affects the urinary tract, causing hematuria and bladder pathology.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Schistosomiasis is characterized by granulomatous inflammation around parasite eggs in affected tissues, particularly the liver, intestines, or urinary tract.","Schistosomiasis can lead to pipe-stem fibrosis of the liver, portal hypertension, and urinary complications including hematuria and calcified bladder.","Different Schistosoma species affect different organ systems: S. mansoni and S. japonicum primarily affect the liver and intestines, while S. haematobium affects the urinary tract."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; pages 397-398."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78930"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20819"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78930"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-31T17:26:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-31T17:27:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id"